<paragraph blockId="6.[189,1398,755,857]" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eppelsheim" authorityYear="1892" box="[189,369,755,781]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novus">
<emphasis box="[189,369,755,781]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Quedius novus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is widely distributed in Middle Asia, where it appears most commonly in southern 
<collectingCountry box="[189,335,792,818]" name="Kazakhstan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Kazakhstan</collectingCountry>
, eastern 
<collectingCountry box="[455,597,792,818]" name="Uzbekistan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Uzbekistan</collectingCountry>
, western 
<collectingCountry box="[724,865,793,819]" name="Kyrgyzstan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Kyrgyzstan</collectingCountry>
and northeastern 
<collectingCountry box="[1102,1223,792,818]" name="Tajikistan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Tajikistan</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A." pageId="6" pageNumber="147" pagination="117 - 159" refId="ref8995" refString="Salnitska M. &amp; Solodovnikov A. 2018 a. Revision of the Quedius fauna of Middle Asia (Coleoptera, Staphylinidae, Staphylininae). Deutsche Entomologische Zeitschrift 65 (2): 117 - 159." type="journal article" year="2018">Salnitska &amp; Solodovnikov 2018a</bibRefCitation>
). Here, we provide the first record of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Eppelsheim" authorityYear="1892" box="[877,981,831,857]" class="Insecta" family="Staphylinidae" genus="Quedius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="6" pageNumber="147" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="novus">
<emphasis box="[877,981,831,857]" italics="true" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Q. novus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<collectingCountry box="[1053,1219,830,856]" name="Turkmenistan" pageId="6" pageNumber="147">Turkmenistan</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
